      <section xml:id="MR-sec-next">
        <title>Next Steps</title>
          <p>
            If you do not feel comfortable completing the above problems 
            on your own, then MA100 is probably the
            right course for you. Return to the Directed Self-Placement 
            and select MA100. On the other hand, if you
            were able to complete 80% of the problems with only minor errors 
            and without assistance, you probably are ready for 
            a different course. 
          </p>
            <p component="nursing">
              Nursing majors who have the skills described above should 
              consider enrolling in <xref ref="ch-QL" text="title"/>. 
            </p> 
            <p component="quant">
              Students considering a major in a quantitative field such as mathematics, cybersecurity,
              biology, computer science, exercise science, or who hope to apply to medical, dental,
              veterinary, or engineering graduate programs should look at 
              evaluate their readiness for <xref ref="ch-CA" text="title"/>
              or <xref ref="ch-Functions" text="title"/>, or a course
                <xref ref="ch-above130" text="custom">above MA130</xref>.
            </p>
            <p component="educ">
              Education majors who can perform the skills in MA100 Math 
              Refresher may choose among several courses to satisfy the 
              general education requirement. The course <xref ref="ch-GeoEx" 
              text="title"/> is designed 
              to strengthen the geometry skills needed to pass the licensure 
              exam, to deepen teachers' understanding of the geometry they will  
              teach, and to experience different ways of teaching. The course 
              <xref ref="ch-Puzzles" text="title"/>
              introduces students to some of the great ideas of mathematics beyond 
              throughout history and explores number systems, infinity, and probability,
              all of which are beneficial for a teacher of mathematics. Students
              who may choose mathematics as their speciality may opt to begin
              with <xref ref="ch-Functions" text="title"/>. 
            </p>
            <p component="gen-ed"> 
            Students who can perform the skills above may choose among several 
            courses that satisfy the general education requirement: The course 
            <xref ref="ch-QL" text="title"/>
            focuses on the mathematics used in making financial and civic decisions.
            The course 
            <xref ref="ch-Puzzles" text="title"/>
            introduces students to some of the great ideas of mathematics beyond 
            throughout history and explores number systems, infinity, and probability. 
            <xref ref="ch-GeoEx" text="title"/>
            encourages students to discover and uncover geometic patterns and 
            understand more deeply geometric ideas, including its appearance in art 
            nature. Students interested in a quantitative field may check their 
            readiness for <xref ref="ch-Functions" text="title"/>.
          </p>
        </section>
